as Kurt Cobain plunged into a spiral
of depression and drug-addiction

33
00:02:22,789 --> 00:02:24,954
that no one could save him from.

34
00:02:27,650 --> 00:02:32,676
I created a project that he had
to flight to Georgia to work with me on,

35
00:02:33,059 --> 00:02:35,923
in an attempt to pull him out of
headspace that he was in in Seattle,

36
00:02:35,994 --> 00:02:38,014
in his house all alone,
but it didn't work.

37
00:02:38,425 --> 00:02:39,591
Sadly.

38
00:02:40,218 --> 00:02:42,859
This is the story of the age
of alternative rock,

39
00:02:43,110 --> 00:02:45,162
when a handful of bands restored

40
00:02:45,232 --> 00:02:48,918
authenticity, meaning
and passion to the music.

41
00:02:49,898 --> 00:02:54,193
And the lasting legacy of the artist
who continues to cast a powerful shadow

42
00:02:54,280 --> 00:02:56,255
over the whole of rock.

43
00:02:56,325 --> 00:02:58,724
Kurt Cobain is the last great rock star,

44
00:02:58,905 --> 00:03:03,596
and I think that's one reason there still
remains so much fascination with him.

45
00:03:06,049 --> 00:03:09,920
<i>An electrician arrived at Kurt Cobain's
luxurious home early in the morning.</i>

46
00:03:10,077 --> 00:03:12,323
<i>... we need to notify the family.</i>

47
00:03:12,358 --> 00:03:16,036
<i>Apparently it was a suicide
at the age of 27.</i>

48
00:03:20,349 --> 00:03:23,636
In the 1980s,
Ronald Reagan's presidency

49
00:03:23,725 --> 00:03:27,410
served up an American dream
of growth and prosperity

50
00:03:28,084 --> 00:03:29,313
for some.

51
00:03:29,583 --> 00:03:31,725
<i>It's morning again in America.</i>

52
00:03:32,156 --> 00:03:34,278
<i>Today more men and women
will go to work</i>

53
00:03:34,279 --> 00:03:36,450
<i>than ever before
in our country's history.</i>

54
00:03:37,211 --> 00:03:38,796
<i>Now you have
everything you wanted.</i>

55
00:03:39,633 --> 00:03:41,281
<i>Including you?</i>

56
00:03:43,472 --> 00:03:45,204
Unless you voted for Reagan,

57
00:03:45,205 --> 00:03:47,925
you didn't have
a great time under Reagan.

58
00:03:48,009 --> 00:03:53,178
It's morning in America for people
who contributed to that campaign,

59
00:03:53,319 --> 00:03:55,117
who shared those ideals.

60
00:03:55,187 --> 00:03:57,255
It wasn't morning in America
for anyone else.

61
00:03:57,315 --> 00:03:58,927
It was like the sun
had just set.

62
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:03,472
# It's the end of the world
as we know it

63
00:04:03,506 --> 00:04:06,146
# and I feel fine

64
00:04:07,528 --> 00:04:11,116
There was an immense frustration
in the country that was palpable

65
00:04:11,194 --> 00:04:15,010
and we certainly shared it
as political activists, as people who...

66
00:04:15,243 --> 00:04:20,639
felt like the very idea of America
was being pulled out from under us.

67
00:04:22,988 --> 00:04:24,207
# The other night I dreamt of knives,

68
00:04:24,286 --> 00:04:26,486
# continental drift divide.
Mountains sit in a line

69
00:04:26,545 --> 00:04:27,967
# Leonard Bernstein...

70
00:04:28,355 --> 00:04:31,872
Reaganomics delivered shock
treatment to the American economy,

71
00:04:31,966 --> 00:04:35,892
sweeping aside the idealism
values of the 1960s.

72
00:04:36,655 --> 00:04:41,478
Those unable or unwilling to conform
were in for a rough ride.

73
00:04:44,684 --> 00:04:46,551
We got no prospects,

74
00:04:46,968 --> 00:04:51,231
you know, what are you gonna do,
work at McDonalds? Deliver papers?

75
00:04:51,339 --> 00:04:54,094
You feel like not only
are you in a minority

76
00:04:54,161 --> 00:04:57,836
but you feel like you're in
a minority nobody gives a shit about.

77
00:04:57,978 --> 00:05:04,842
# Well a person can work up
a mean mean thirst

78
00:05:05,127 --> 00:05:10,377
# After a hard day
of nothin' much at all

79
00:05:10,460 --> 00:05:13,901
In the depressed logging town
of Aberdeen in Washington St.,

80
00:05:13,940 --> 00:05:16,730
Kurt Cobain was part
of that minority.

81
00:05:16,881 --> 00:05:19,396
A high-school dropout
from a broken home,

82
00:05:19,557 --> 00:05:24,588
Kurt entered a downsize world
of dead end jobs in 1985.

83
00:05:24,684 --> 00:05:27,243
He ended up getting a job
back at the high school

84
00:05:27,351 --> 00:05:30,542
that he had dropped out of.
He was the janitor.

85
00:05:30,620 --> 00:05:33,821
So you can imagine the shame
that he must have felt of

86
00:05:33,881 --> 00:05:38,636
coming in the halls and seeing kids that
were his classmates just months before,

87
00:05:38,704 --> 00:05:42,695
and they're going off to college
and what he's doing is mopping the floor.

88
00:05:43,997 --> 00:05:46,190
Kurt's experience was not unique.

89
00:05:46,556 --> 00:05:50,208
He was part of "Generation X",
children who felt alienated

90
00:05:50,311 --> 00:05:53,104
and excluded from
conventional society,

91
00:05:53,177 --> 00:05:55,009
who would never enjoy the prospects

92
00:05:55,088 --> 00:05:58,141
their baby-boomer parents
had taken for granted.

93
00:06:00,293 --> 00:06:02,675
Kurt would find a soulmate in Aberdeen,

94
00:06:02,725 --> 00:06:05,106
who shared a similar
background and outlook,

95
00:06:05,775 --> 00:06:07,556
Krist Novoselic.

96
00:06:07,582 --> 00:06:12,295
A lot of it had to do with our
personal situations, family things and

97
00:06:12,768 --> 00:06:18,416
maybe ideals and promises broken.

98
00:06:18,479 --> 00:06:22,510
It boiled down to alienation
and recognising

99
00:06:22,618 --> 00:06:25,843
we'd look at the mainstream culture

100
00:06:25,844 --> 00:06:30,267
and see that it didn't
have a lot to offer us.

101
00:06:34,167 --> 00:06:37,448
The real lives and emotions
of America's alienated youth

102
00:06:37,636 --> 00:06:40,487
weren't reflected
in the studio polished rock

103
00:06:40,555 --> 00:06:44,306
that filled mainstream radio
and MTV.

104
00:06:45,519 --> 00:06:49,036
# But what I need to make me tight are

105
00:06:49,089 --> 00:06:51,379
# Girls, Girls, Girls

106
00:06:52,915 --> 00:06:55,518
# Long legs and burgundy lips

107
00:06:55,847 --> 00:06:59,723
I was not getting what I needed
from Ted Nugent.

108
00:06:59,807 --> 00:07:02,535
I was a young guy going
to a school I hated,

109
00:07:02,589 --> 00:07:05,844
like a lot of young men,
you hate the school, the teachers,

110
00:07:05,893 --> 00:07:07,141
you want to burn the place
to the ground,

111
00:07:07,196 --> 00:07:14,270
and you want something or
someone to represent that for you.

112
00:07:14,342 --> 00:07:17,465
Van Halen sang about girls...
Fine!

113
00:07:17,815 --> 00:07:23,677
But there wasn't the "white riot,
I wanna riot" thing happening.

114
00:07:23,804 --> 00:07:27,110
And there was no sense
of dislocation in that music,

115
00:07:27,165 --> 00:07:29,934
where I... I'm out.
I hate all of y'all.

116
00:07:30,463 --> 00:07:34,243
Henry Rollins' search for an alternative
would lead him to join a band

117
00:07:34,307 --> 00:07:37,313
whose fearsome reputation
would thrill and inspire

118
00:07:37,342 --> 00:07:39,620
Kurt Cobain and Krist Novoselic,

119
00:07:40,189 --> 00:07:41,794
Black Flag.

120
00:07:47,842 --> 00:07:50,986
<i>I got a six-pack,
and nothing to do.</i>

121
00:07:51,470 --> 00:07:58,159
I actually went to see Black Flag play
in Walla Walla, Washington, in 1984.

122
00:07:58,214 --> 00:08:02,127
And they had this idea that
they were gonna tour the hinterlands

123
00:08:02,167 --> 00:08:04,878
and bring the message to the people.

124
00:08:04,953 --> 00:08:06,639
And it was amazing.

125
00:08:06,717 --> 00:08:09,144
# Thirty-five dollars
and a six pack to my name

126
00:08:09,615 --> 00:08:10,917
# Six-pack!

127
00:08:10,982 --> 00:08:13,452
# Spent the rest on beer
so who's to blame

128
00:08:13,693 --> 00:08:14,633
# Six-pack!

129
00:08:14,776 --> 00:08:19,222
Black Flag played an adrenaline charged
brand of punk known as 'hard core',

130
00:08:19,490 --> 00:08:23,281
a sound that captured the frustration
and rage experienced by many

131
00:08:23,338 --> 00:08:25,237
growing up in Reagan's America.

132
00:08:27,055 --> 00:08:30,325
# I got a six pack in me alright!

133
00:08:30,379 --> 00:08:34,067
It was this post-punk,
letting out that angst,

134
00:08:34,128 --> 00:08:38,573
and just that very honest
fury of youth

135
00:08:38,612 --> 00:08:45,318
and all that confusion and pain
into this very short bursts of music.

136
00:08:46,162 --> 00:08:48,683
# Now I got a six so I'll never run out

137
00:08:48,722 --> 00:08:49,899
# Six pack!

138
00:08:50,020 --> 00:08:53,859
Some people are gonna listen to
Black Flag and they're gonna love it,

139
00:08:53,913 --> 00:08:57,124
and some people...
it's gonna scare them.

140
00:08:57,537 --> 00:09:00,257
Black Flag earned the reputation
of staging shows

141
00:09:00,320 --> 00:09:02,919
which frequently descended
into violence.

142
00:09:04,921 --> 00:09:06,074
# Six pack!

143
00:09:07,226 --> 00:09:09,145
<i>What do they know
about partying?</i>

144
00:09:09,381 --> 00:09:10,773
<i>Or anything else?</i>

145
00:09:15,263 --> 00:09:16,802
He runs this place.

146
00:09:16,864 --> 00:09:20,164
You'd set up to play in some town
and then here comes the mayor,

147
00:09:20,217 --> 00:09:24,497
and a news team, and a reverend.

148
00:09:24,676 --> 00:09:27,565
And here comes the Christians
protesting and lighting candles,

149
00:09:27,624 --> 00:09:30,453
going like, "Oh my God! No!
Help our children!"

150
00:09:30,768 --> 00:09:32,889
# I don't care what's inside

151
00:09:34,289 --> 00:09:37,069
# We're not gonna kill you!

152
00:09:37,868 --> 00:09:40,819
We're like four starving
vegetarians in a van,

153
00:09:40,874 --> 00:09:43,144
so they're ready for
this fire-breathing beast,

154
00:09:43,222 --> 00:09:45,923
and we're like, "Hi, we're Black Flag.
We hate everyone"

155
00:09:47,063 --> 00:09:48,512
<i>It's all right ma'm.
They've gone.</i>

156
00:09:52,389 --> 00:09:53,756
# Gimme, gimme, gimme

157
00:09:54,031 --> 00:09:55,702
# I need some more

158
00:09:55,757 --> 00:09:58,170
Finding somewhere to play
was a challenge for the bands

159
00:09:58,224 --> 00:10:00,014
on the growing alternative scene.

160
00:10:00,183 --> 00:10:02,798
Unable to fill cavernous
arenas and ballrooms,

161
00:10:02,853 --> 00:10:05,508
they had to create their
own improvised circuit.

162
00:10:07,738 --> 00:10:10,112
What Black Flag had to do
was basically

163
00:10:10,197 --> 00:10:13,081
blaze their own trail,
and they cobbled together

164
00:10:13,165 --> 00:10:17,155
this kind of underground
railroad of indie rock.

165
00:10:17,892 --> 00:10:21,782
All across America, a whole generation
of alternative rock bands

166
00:10:21,857 --> 00:10:23,597
from Black Flag to R.E.M

167
00:10:23,647 --> 00:10:28,248
came of age in venues as eclectic
as the bands themselves.

168
00:10:29,137 --> 00:10:33,518
There was a small circuit of
clubs, pizza parlors and gay bars

169
00:10:33,573 --> 00:10:37,287
and tiny places around the country
that would open their doors

170
00:10:37,345 --> 00:10:41,320
and have really shitty sound systems
and let these bands play.

171
00:10:42,407 --> 00:10:46,310
There were times when Black Flag would
play on a Friday and R.E.M. on a Saturday

172
00:10:46,359 --> 00:10:48,356
and the next week we'd play the Friday
and they'd play the Saturday.

173
00:10:48,409 --> 00:10:50,587
We were chasing each other for years.

174
00:10:51,282 --> 00:10:52,827
And pretty soon there was a circuit.

175
00:10:52,936 --> 00:10:54,938
And when there's a circuit
there's a scene.

176
00:10:55,015 --> 00:10:56,946
And when there's a scene
there's a community.

177
00:10:57,024 --> 00:11:01,285
And when there's a community then
you've got something really interesting.

178
00:11:01,597 --> 00:11:04,568
That community united
a wide variety of bands

179
00:11:04,608 --> 00:11:07,947
who shared the same independent spirit
and circumstances,

180
00:11:07,999 --> 00:11:11,872
and a fierce determination
to make it on their own terms.

181
00:11:15,137 --> 00:11:21,123
Touring bands in a van get by.
And what do you get in return?

182
00:11:21,182 --> 00:11:23,559
300 hundred sweaty,
adoring fans a night,

183
00:11:23,794 --> 00:11:26,309
and your freedom,
your musical freedom.

184
00:11:26,363 --> 00:11:28,108
And maybe you missed some meals

185
00:11:28,442 --> 00:11:31,141
or the cops came and
shut your show down,

186
00:11:31,289 --> 00:11:37,970
but man, you weren't flipping burgers,
and you weren't filling slurpies.

187
00:11:38,176 --> 00:11:40,362
And there was something
to be said for that.

188
00:11:41,014 --> 00:11:45,584
Life on the road was an essential rite of
passage for all alternative rock bands.

189
00:11:45,661 --> 00:11:49,329
But for R.E.M,
a band that had formed in 1980,

190
00:11:49,396 --> 00:11:52,212
in the tiny university
town of Athens, Georgia,

191
00:11:52,275 --> 00:11:56,250
it would also prove to be a springboard
to far greater success.

192
00:11:56,358 --> 00:12:01,406
And it began with a song inspired
by a cold war radio station,

193
00:12:01,431 --> 00:12:04,067
<i>Radio Free Europe
calls on Presov.</i>

194
00:12:04,125 --> 00:12:06,664
# Calling all in transit,
calling all in transit

195
00:12:06,728 --> 00:12:09,566
# Calling all in transit,
calling all in transit

196
00:12:09,605 --> 00:12:14,069
# Radio free Europe, radio...

197
00:12:14,953 --> 00:12:19,003
'Radio Free Europe' instantly laid out
the R.E.M. blueprint.

198
00:12:20,824 --> 00:12:23,251
Peter Buck chiming guitar chords,

199
00:12:23,367 --> 00:12:26,731
Mike Mills and Bill Berry's
energetic rhythm section,

200
00:12:27,143 --> 00:12:31,270
but it would be Michael Stipe's
enigmatic vocals and performances

201
00:12:31,357 --> 00:12:33,556
that became the band's
early trademark.

202
00:12:33,648 --> 00:12:37,011
# That this isn't country at all

203
00:12:37,170 --> 00:12:40,675
I was just an incredibly shy person
and not terribly confident.

204
00:12:40,739 --> 00:12:46,117
I had terrible acne and used my hair
to cover my face a lot.

205
00:12:46,165 --> 00:12:48,268
I mumbled when I talked
and mumbled when I sang.

206
00:12:48,318 --> 00:12:54,832
So all that combined into what I guess
came across as some modicum of charisma.

207
00:12:54,848 --> 00:12:57,047
And people were very
taken by it.

208
00:12:57,100 --> 00:12:59,460
# Calling all in transit,
calling all in transit

209
00:12:59,499 --> 00:13:02,324
# Calling all in transit,
calling all in transit

210
00:13:02,368 --> 00:13:07,123
# Radio free Europe, radio...

211
00:13:07,668 --> 00:13:12,357
Michael Stipe's mystique helped make
'Radio Free Europe' a critical hit,

212
00:13:12,459 --> 00:13:14,978
as the new breed of bands began
to receive airplay

213
00:13:15,043 --> 00:13:17,209
on another alternative network,

214
00:13:17,267 --> 00:13:18,793
'Call It Radio'.

215
00:13:20,014 --> 00:13:25,758
# Read about your band
in some local page

216
00:13:25,998 --> 00:13:31,200
# Didn't mention your name,
didn't mention your name

217
00:13:34,151 --> 00:13:39,859
It was that separate world of what
is now called alternative rock,

218
00:13:39,971 --> 00:13:42,452
which at the time was only
called college rock

219
00:13:42,511 --> 00:13:46,984
because the only place you heard it
on the radio was on college stations,

220
00:13:47,052 --> 00:13:49,356
it's the classic Replacements' song
'Left of the Dial'.

221
00:13:50,191 --> 00:13:51,872
# ...in a long, long while

222
00:13:53,187 --> 00:13:55,405
# I'll try to find you

223
00:13:55,665 --> 00:13:58,671
# Left of the dial

224
00:13:59,058 --> 00:14:01,570
# Left of the dial

225
00:14:02,328 --> 00:14:06,128
It's a song about where
you tuned manually,

226
00:14:06,257 --> 00:14:09,099
you turned the little knob
to the left of the dial,

227
00:14:09,231 --> 00:14:11,696
to the 88.9s and the 90.1s,

228
00:14:11,795 --> 00:14:13,810
all the stuff that was below
the commercial band.

229
00:14:15,774 --> 00:14:18,345
You had to look for it,

230
00:14:18,452 --> 00:14:22,335
and people who really wanted
something more out of music,

231
00:14:22,447 --> 00:14:25,989
who wanted more out of life,
something more out of their guitars,

232
00:14:26,237 --> 00:14:28,170
that's where you went.

233
00:14:32,758 --> 00:14:35,368
As more and more people
turned to the left of the dial

234
00:14:35,452 --> 00:14:38,970
they discovered that even fast
and furious alternative rock bands,

235
00:14:39,088 --> 00:14:43,814
such as Hüsker Dü were, like R.E.M.,
embracing melody and harmony.

